ption handling may terminate processing or fail to increment/report skipped count. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: no required real OS/network/subprocess; no AI dependency; no multi-step agent pipeline. REJECTION-GATE: rejected System because behavior text is about JSON handling and pipeline resilience, which is reproducible fully in-process.","test_description":"Run ingestion pipeline modules with a mixed stream of valid and malformed JSON entries; assert processing continues, valid entries are still emitted, and skipped-entry count equals malformed-entry count in the final report/output metrics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA: this is a throughput/backpressure/runtime behavior that depends on real process scheduling, buffering, and I/O timing characteristics. MOCK-HIDE: in-process fakes can hide queue saturation, scheduler contention, GC pauses, and actual sink throughput limits. LOWER-LEVEL-MISS-PROOF (why above Unit): unit tests cannot expose end-to-end burst backpressure or drop behavior across pipeline stages. LOWER-LEVEL-MISS-PROOF (why above Integration): integration with mocked/fake time or in-memory stubs can pass while real runtime under sustained 10k/s drops messages or accumulates lag. REJECTION-GATE: rejected Agentic/Workflow because no LLM/model decisions are involved.","test_description":"Run the real executable/service pipeline under a burst load generator at 10,000 entries/sec with real queues/sinks used in deployment-equivalent config; assert ingested count equals emitted+accounted count, no unbounded lag growth, and sustained processing keeps pace over the test window.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0